{"title_page": "Naima Ramos-Chapman", "text_new": "{{short description|American filmmaker}}\n'''Naima Ramos-Chapman''' is an American writer, actress, and filmmaker. She directed two short films that deal with [[Gender violence|gender-based violence]], ''And Nothing Happened'' in 2016, and ''Piu Piu'' in 2018. She is slated to direct the pilot for [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s upcoming comedy series, ''How to Make Love to a Black Woman (Who May Be Working Through Some Sh*t)''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/random-acts-of-flyness-naima-ramos-chapman-on-directing-writing-and-editing-for-hbo-1202145569/|title=\u2018Random Acts of Flyness\u2019: Naima Ramos-Chapman on Directing, Writing, and Editing for HBO|last=Travers|first=Ben|last2=Travers|first2=Ben|date=2019-05-30|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/naima-ramos-chapman-to-direct-showtime-pilot-how-to-make-love-to-a-black-woman-1202652501/|title=Naima Ramos-Chapman To Direct Showtime Pilot \u2018How To Make Love To A Black Woman\u2019|last=Petski|first=Denise|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=2019-07-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nRamos-Chapman was raised in [[Flatbush, Brooklyn|Flatbush]], Brooklyn.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturedmag.com/naima-ramos-chapman/|title=Filmmaker Naima Ramos-Chapman Subverts Expectations|date=2019-02-18|website=Cultured Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> She is of Puerto Rican and Black descent.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://nylon.com/articles/naima-ramos-chapman-random-acts-flyness-interview|title=Naima Ramos-Chapman Wants Men To Take Responsibility For Themselves|date=2018-09-04|website=NYLON|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> She studied dance from childhood and attended the Alvin Ailey School for Dance. Ramos-Chapman graduated from [[Brooklyn College]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/culture/naima-ramos-chapman-and-nothing-happened-filmmaker-kickstarter/|title=How Filmmaker Naima Ramos-Chapman Used Kickstarter to Fund Her Debut Short Film|website=Essence|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\nThe first film Ramos-Chapman wrote and directed was the 2016 short ''And Nothing Happened''.<ref name=\":2\" /> She used [[Kickstarter]] and worked several jobs to finance the film.<ref name=\":5\" /> The film, which she stars in, was inspired by her trauma in the aftermath of a sexual assault.<ref name=\":4\" /> She stated in an interview with ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'', \"It is not only a thing one person survives\u2013sexual assault is something a whole family, community, nation survives and until we understand that we cannot truly confront it. That is why I made ''And Nothing Happened''.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2018, Ramos-Chapman wrote and directed ''Piu Piu'', a \"psycho surrealist\" short that premiered at the 2018 [[BlackStar Film Festival]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/10/they-seem-cool-filmmaker-naima-ramos-chapman.html|title=The Filmmaker With Empathy for Cersei Lannister|last=Spellings|first=Diana Tsui, Sarah|date=2018-10-18|website=The Cut|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> ''Piu Piu'' is loosely based on an experience Ramos-Chapman had being stalked by a stranger in public.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRamos-Chapman was a writer, director, and actor for HBO's ''[[Random Acts of Flyness]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> She also edits and does production work for the series.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn July 24, 2019, it was announced that Ramos-Chapman will direct the upcoming Showtime series ''How to Make Love to a Black Woman (Who May Be Working Through Some Sh*t).'' The series is executive produced by [[Lena Waithe]] and written by creator Casallina \u201cCathy\u201d Kisakye.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is in a relationship with [[Terence Nance]], who she met while interviewing him for Saint Heron, the creative agency owned by [[Solange Knowles]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[[imdbname:5774032|Naima Ramos-Chapman]] on IMDb\n*[https://www.naimaramoschapman.com/ Official website]\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramos-Chapman, Naima}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American directors]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican film directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Filmmakers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Flatbush, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American filmmaker}}\n'''Naima Ramos-Chapman''' is an American writer, actress, and filmmaker. She directed two short films that deal with [[Gender violence|gender-based violence]], ''And Nothing Happened'' in 2016, and ''Piu Piu'' in 2018. She is slated to direct the pilot for [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s upcoming comedy series, ''How to Make Love to a Black Woman (Who May Be Working Through Some Sh*t)''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/random-acts-of-flyness-naima-ramos-chapman-on-directing-writing-and-editing-for-hbo-1202145569/|title=\u2018Random Acts of Flyness\u2019: Naima Ramos-Chapman on Directing, Writing, and Editing for HBO|last=Travers|first=Ben|last2=Travers|first2=Ben|date=2019-05-30|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/naima-ramos-chapman-to-direct-showtime-pilot-how-to-make-love-to-a-black-woman-1202652501/|title=Naima Ramos-Chapman To Direct Showtime Pilot \u2018How To Make Love To A Black Woman\u2019|last=Petski|first=Denise|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=2019-07-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n== Life & career ==\nRamos-Chapman was raised in [[Flatbush, Brooklyn|Flatbush]], Brooklyn.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturedmag.com/naima-ramos-chapman/|title=Filmmaker Naima Ramos-Chapman Subverts Expectations|date=2019-02-18|website=Cultured Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> She is of Puerto Rican and Black descent.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://nylon.com/articles/naima-ramos-chapman-random-acts-flyness-interview|title=Naima Ramos-Chapman Wants Men To Take Responsibility For Themselves|date=2018-09-04|website=NYLON|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> She studied dance from childhood and attended the Alvin Ailey School for Dance. Ramos-Chapman graduated from [[Brooklyn College]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/culture/naima-ramos-chapman-and-nothing-happened-filmmaker-kickstarter/|title=How Filmmaker Naima Ramos-Chapman Used Kickstarter to Fund Her Debut Short Film|website=Essence|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\nThe first film Ramos-Chapman wrote and directed was the 2016 short ''And Nothing Happened''.<ref name=\":2\" /> She used Kickstarter and worked several jobs to finance the film.<ref name=\":5\" /> The film, which she stars in, was inspired by her trauma in the aftermath of a sexual assault.<ref name=\":4\" /> She stated in an interview with ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'', \"It is not only a thing one person survives\u2013sexual assault is something a whole family, community, nation survives and until we understand that we cannot truly confront it. That is why I made ''And Nothing Happened''.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2018, Ramos-Chapman wrote and directed ''Piu Piu'', a \"psycho surrealist\" short that premiered at the 2018 [[BlackStar Film Festival]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/10/they-seem-cool-filmmaker-naima-ramos-chapman.html|title=The Filmmaker With Empathy for Cersei Lannister|last=Spellings|first=Diana Tsui, Sarah|date=2018-10-18|website=The Cut|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> ''Piu Piu'' is loosely based on an experience Ramos-Chapman had being stalked by a stranger in public, while And Nothing Happened was inspired by her trauma in the aftermath of a sexual assault.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRamos-Chapman was a writer, director, and actor for HBO's ''[[Random Acts of Flyness]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> She also edits and does production work for the series.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn July 24, 2019, it was announced that Ramos-Chapman will direct the upcoming Showtime series ''How to Make Love to a Black Woman (Who May Be Working Through Some Sh*t).'' The series is executive produced by [[Lena Waithe]] and written by creator Casallina \u201cCathy\u201d Kisakye.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is in a relationship with [[Terence Nance]], who she met while interviewing him for Saint Heron, the creative agency owned by [[Solange Knowles]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[[imdbname:5774032|Naima Ramos-Chapman]] on IMDb\n*[https://www.naimaramoschapman.com/ Official website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramos-Chapman, Naima}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American directors]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican film directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Filmmakers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Flatbush, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Br